{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532164"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14654"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.7,0.08,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102440"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84914"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4041"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102440"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right-sided pleuritic chest pain and mild shortness of breath. He has metastatic prostate cancer diagnosed eight months ago with bone metastases, currently receiving androgen deprivation therapy. He has no other significant medical history. His only regular medications are goserelin and calcium supplements. He lives at home with his wife and remains fully independent with his activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His chest is clear to auscultation. There is mild tenderness to palpation over the right lateral chest wall. His calves are soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show haemoglobin 118 g/L (130-170), white cell count 6.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0), and platelets 145 x 10^9/L (150-400). His computed tomography pulmonary angiogram reveals multiple subsegmental pulmonary emboli in both lower lobes with no evidence of right heart strain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prophylactic dose anticoagulation","Therapeutic anticoagulation","Clinical surveillance without anticoagulation","Thrombolysis","Inferior vena cava filter insertion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with metastatic prostate cancer and multiple subsegmental pulmonary emboli requires prompt and effective management to reduce the risk of further embolic events and complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This patient has multiple subsegmental pulmonary emboli against active cancer. Hence, the risk of clot progression and recurrence is significant. Therapeutic anticoagulation, typically with low molecular weight heparin or a direct oral anticoagulant, is recommended unless there are absolute contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic dose anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for treating pulmonary emboli. Prophylactic dosing may be used for prevention, not for treatment of acute events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical surveillance without anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in select patients with isolated, symptomatic subsegmental pulmonary embolism and a high risk of bleeding or absolute contraindication to anticoagulation. However, this patient has multiple emboli and active cancer, both of which increase the risk of progression and recurrence, making observation inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for people with massive pulmonary embolism and haemodynamic instability. This patient is haemodynamically stable and has no evidence of right heart strain, so thrombolysis is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior vena cava filter insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is considered only when there are absolute contraindications to anticoagulation. There is no such contraindication in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with active cancer are at increased risk of venous thromboembolism.","While some patients with isolated, symptomatic subsegmental pulmonary embolism and contraindications to anticoagulation may undergo active surveillance, this patient has active cancer and multiple emboli, necessitating therapeutic anticoagulation."],"references":["Lyman GH, Carrier M, Ay C, Di Nisio M, Hicks LK, Khorana AA, Leavitt AD, Lee AY, Macbeth F, Morgan RL, Noble S. American Society of Hematology 2021 guidelines for management of venous thromboembolism: prevention and treatment in patients with cancer. Blood advances. 2021 Feb 23;5(4):927-74. Available online at ; https://ashpublications.org/bloodadvances/article/5/4/927/475194/American-Society-of-Hematology-2021-guidelines-for","Kruger PC, Eikelboom JW, Douketis JD, Hankey GJ. Pulmonary embolism: update on diagnosis and management. Med J Aust. 2019;211(2):82-87. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31216072/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84914"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14654"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84914"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T18:56:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T18:57:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7347"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102440"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t